
[1]gooseberry

   GOOSEBERRY, n. goos'berry. [L. grossula. The English word is
   undoubtedly corrupted from crossberry, grossberry, or gorseberry; a
   name taken from the roughness of the shrub. See Cross and Gross.]

   The fruit of a shrub, and the shrub itself, the Ribes grossularia. The
   shrub is armed with spines. Of the fruit there are several varieties.

   The American gooseberry belongs to the genus Melastoma, and the West
   Indian, gooseberry to the genus Cactus.
